04397nam a22005415i 9780520927285DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209272857 a10.1525/97805209272852doi  a(DE-B1597)520846  a(OCoLC)1096468709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aTX641b.A36 2002eb 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a641 .01 32211 aAlbala, Ken, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEating Right in the Renaissance /cKen Albala. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Spelling -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Overview of the Genre -- tChapter 2. The Human Body: Humors, Digestion, and the Physiology of Nutrition -- tChapter 3. Food: Qualities, Substance, and Virtues -- tChapter 4. External Factors -- tChapter 5. Food and the Individual -- tChapter 6. Food and Class -- tChapter 7. Food and Nation -- tChapter 8. Medicine and Cuisine -- tPostscript: The End of a Genre and Its Legacy -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEating right has been an obsession for longer than we think. Renaissance Europe had its own flourishing tradition of dietary advice. Then, as now, an industry of experts churned out diet books for an eager and concerned public. Providing a cornucopia of information on food and an intriguing account of the differences between the nutritional logic of the past and our own time, this inviting book examines the wide-ranging dietary literature of the Renaissance. Ken Albala ultimately reveals the working of the Renaissance mind from a unique perspective: we come to understand a people through their ideas on food.Eating Right in the Renaissance takes us through an array of historical sources in a narrative that is witty and spiced with fascinating details. Why did early Renaissance writers recommend the herbs parsley, arugula, anise, and mint to fortify sexual prowess? Why was there such a strong outcry against melons and cucumbers, even though people continued to eat them in large quantities? Why was wine considered a necessary nutrient? As he explores these and other questions, Albala explains the history behind Renaissance dietary theories; the connections among food, exercise, and sex; the changing relationship between medicine and cuisine; and much more. Whereas modern nutritionists may promise a slimmer waistline, more stamina, or freedom from disease, Renaissance food writers had entirely different ideas about the value of eating right. As he uncovers these ideas from the past, Ken Albala puts our own dietary obsessions in an entirely new light in this elegantly written and often surprising new chapter on the history of food.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFood habitszEuropexHistory. 0aGastronomy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520927285.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles